<li id="cite_note-8"><b><a href="#cite_ref-8" title="">^</a></b> Xenophon, (1986) p.184</li>
<li id="cite_note-9"><b><a href="#cite_ref-9" title="">^</a></b> See Lazenby (2004) pp.149-153, in relation to the deprivations of Cyracusian Cavalry and counter-methods</li>
<li id="cite_note-10"><b><a href="#cite_ref-10" title="">^</a></b> See Xenophon (1986) pp.157-161 "The Greeks Suffer From Slings and Arrows", and the methods improvised to solve this problem</li>
<li id="cite_note-11"><b><a href="#cite_ref-11" title="">^</a></b> Wees (2004) p.189</li>
<li id="cite_note-12"><b><a href="#cite_ref-12" title="">^</a></b> Goldsworthy, p.102</li>
<li id="cite_note-13"><b><a href="#cite_ref-13" title="">^</a></b> Lendon, J.E., <i>Soldiers &amp; Ghosts: A History of Battle in Classical Antiquity</i>, Yale University Press (2005), <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0300119798" class="internal">ISBN 0300119798</a>, 9780300119794, p. 182: The phalanx was known to the Romans in pre-Republic days, whose best fighting men were armed as hoplites.</li>
<li id="cite_note-14"><b><a href="#cite_ref-14" title="">^</a></b> Lendon, J.E., <i>Soldiers &amp; Ghosts: A History of Battle in Classical Antiquity</i>, Yale University Press (2005), <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0300119798" class="internal">ISBN 0300119798</a>, 9780300119794, pp. 182-183</li>
</ol>
</div>
